-> The Flyweight Pattern is a Structural Design Pattern that reduces memory usage by sharing common 
objects instead of creating duplicate objects.
-> The Flyweight Pattern is used when a large number of similar objects are created. Instead of 
creating a new object every time, it shares the common data between multiple objects to save memory.

-> Sometimes an application creates thousands or even millions of objects. Many of these objects 
contain the same information. Creating separate objects for identical data wastes memory and reduces 
performance.

#Intrinsic vs Extrinsic State

1. Intrinsic State (Shared)
    - Intrinsic state is the information that is common for all objects and never changes.

- Examples: 

1. For Tree
    Texture
    Color
    Height
    Width

2. For Character
    Font
    Size
    Style

This data is stored inside the Flyweight object.


2. Extrinsic State (Unique)
    - Extrinsic state is the information that changes for every object.
    
- Examples:
For Tree
    X Position
    Y Position

For Character
    Character Position

This data is provided by the client whenever needed.